t distinct social needs while making money. Do these types of businesses have the potential for growth in the modern economy? Are they destined to function only in areas where conventional firms cannot achieve a sufficient rate of return? Or will the role of social economy organizations change as businesses begin placing more emphasis on corporate social responsibility?Building on the popular 2010 collection Researching the Social Economy, Businesses with a Difference explores the challenges and opportunities faced by firms that seek a genuine balance between their social and economic objectives. Through international case studies, including comparative analyses, this innovative collection highlights the unique issues that must be addressed when associations are accountable not to investors and shareholders, but instead to ordinary people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCooperative societiesvCase studies. 0aCooperative societiesxCanada. 0aCooperative societiesxCase studies. 0aCooperative societieszCanada. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspectsxCanada. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aEconomicszCanadaxSociological aspects. 0aNonprofit organizationsvCase studies. 0aNonprofit organizationsxCanada. 0aNonprofit organizationsxCase studies. 0aNonprofit organizationszCanada. 0aSocial entrepreneurshipvCase studies. 0aSocial entrepreneurshipxCanada. 0aSocial entrepreneurshipxCase studies. 0aSocial entrepreneurshipzCanada. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh1 aBrouard, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCid, Mikel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruner, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalseth, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab